_data.title: Old Lady Who Lived In A Shoe
Classic City Eats

children.value: Classic City Eats is a chicken restaurant with a focus on southern flavor. After stepping away from their old name and identity as a franchised restauraunt, they adopted the nickname of the "Classic City" of Athens, Georgia and needed a branding update to match. They wanted a logo and accompanying menu that would really embody the spirit of the city.

Starting with the logo, I took note of an Athenian staple and explored different types of neon signs for inspiration. I really wanted the logo to scream Athens, so I used one of the city’s most recognizable buildings: City Hall. I paired it with a font that was bold, but had a 50s diner vibe. The result was as Classic as it was Athens.

I carried the type selection into the menu, settling on the city's prominent red and black palette to inform the flow of information on the page. Leaving the menu content at a base black, I displayed the prominent design elements as well as the headings and important subheadings in a vibrant red. By putting a mock skyline of the city’s most popular buildings, I reinforced the hometown feel of the restaurant.
Classic City Eats was able to build on the foundational visual indentity I provided them and have since evolved past their franchise beginning, building a great reputation in the community.
Crafted with Adobe InDesign and Adobe Illustrator

_data.title: Homestar

children.value: Homestar was looking to send out a seasonal mailer to entice customers into purchasing a home. The client gave me the freedom to do just about anything I wanted with the design, with the only restrictions being to use the company's choice of blue and - of course - their logo. I interspersed autumn imagery with the housing photos to evoke the warm feeling of home.

_data.title: Lowe Electric Supply

children.value: Lowe Electric is an electrical supply company with locations all over Georgia. They were looking to make a large-format wall calendar that they could distribute to their customers.

One feature they wanted me to implement was a continuous numbering for each day of the year throughout the calendar. I also added a lined block for their clients to write in their own notes. Each page of the calendar features the locations and phone number for every Lowe Electric in the state. As a final feature, I also added a year-at-a-glance for each page. Lowe Electric was able to please their clients with a smart, clean and functional calendar that also represented their existing brand perfectly.

_data.description: Full Conference Program, Nametags, & Reception Tickets
_data.title: 5th Annual Linguistics Conference at the University of Georgia

children.value: The organizers of the 5th Annual Linguistics Conference at the University of Georgia needed a full suite of items to support their conference. This included a poster, a full event program with abstracts and schedules, name badges for all organizers and presenters, and event tickets for the post-conference reception. This project presented a unique challenge: How do I provide an eye-catching design that didn’t burden the conference’s budget constraints?

The solution I arrived at was to rely on layout and typographic elements printed on brightly colored paper. Printing solid black on neon sheets was not only cost-effective, it also permitted the design to incorporate bright colors that are nearly impossible to reproduce through the regular digital printing process. Relying on the paper in this way also allowed the design to be multi-modal: it can be printed on different colored backings, either to create visual interest, or - in the case of the nametags - to differentiate conference speaker and organizer name badges.

_data.title: Rainbow Star Farms

children.value: Rainbow Star Farm is a small farm located in Gainesville, Florida. As they were starting a new community-supported agriculture (CSA) program, they were looking to give their farm a professional redesign to entice the local student population. Needing a way to get the word out about the CSA, and hoping to show off their seasonal produce, they requested an eye-catching and informative flyer to communicate the program goals. One aspect of their program they were sure to emphasize was their free-range eggs, produced by their lovely chickens - who I got to meet! I wanted to make the chickens the star of the show, and so I represented them front-and-center in the farm's fun new logo.
